        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We chose the lowest resolution correlator setting to detect the CO(6-5) line. This resolution is good enough for our scientific pupose as mentioned  above. We also put 3 additional basebands with the lowest resolution correlator setting for the calibration purpose.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In order to model the lens system, we need to identify distinct star-forming clumps in the lensed source to use as constraints.  The typical separation of clumps is ~1 kpc (~0.1" at the source redshift) based on source reconstructions of SDP.81 (e.g., Tamura et al. 2015, Rybak et al. 2015, Dye et al. 2015), as well as other lensed sub-mm sources at similar redshifts (e.g., Jones et al. 2010).  Therefore, we set our target angular resolution to be 0.05" FWHM in order to be able to resolve distinct features in the lensed images.

The largest angular scale is set by the expected thickness of the lensed image.  Assuming a source half-light radius of 0.16" (Bussmann et al. 2013) and that the lensing magnification is entirely in the tangential direction, we set the largest angular scale to be 0.3", roughly twice the expected thickness of the lensed arc.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have run simulations with realistic core radii and SMBH masses to predict how well we will be able to constrain the SMBH mass for an observation at a particular S/N. We find that we need a 10-sigma detection of the central image in CO(J=6-5) to properly estimate the SMBH mass.

We request 70 km/s as the velocity width for line detection, but we are configured to have a Nyquist sampling of 35 km/s as the velocity resolution needed to separate out the different molecular clouds in the lensed source as mentioned in the Scientific Justification.  This velocity resolution should be sufficient to resolve different clumps in the source galaxy, as star-forming galaxies around z~2 have velocity dispersions of order 100-200 km/s (e.g., Genzel et al. 2011).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
